{"actual_usd":0.159785,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":263,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"No—if you mean the Christian center of it, the death was real.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square a second, wanting to say it cleanly without turning it into mush.* \"Not 'God stopped being God,' and not 'the divinity ducked out so only a shell got hurt.' The claim is stranger and heavier than that: the Son truly took on human nature, and in that human nature he truly suffered and truly died.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"A lot of the early fights were exactly over that point. If Jesus only seemed to suffer, or if the divine part bailed before the cross, then the Cross starts turning into theater. Christianity rejected that. The body wasn't a costume.\"\n\n\"The usual way Christians say it is that Christ is one person with two natures—fully God and fully man. So his human body really died. His human soul really departed from his body, the way death is for man. But the person undergoing that death was still the eternal Son.\" *I make a small face.* \"Which is why it bends your brain a little.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short version of how the church answered this from Scripture and the councils, without drowning you in jargon.\"","rolling_24h_usd":82.428315,"run_id":"85ecea1a-a72d-45f5-be73-4ea1a4bbb055"}
